The worst fears about Warehouse 13 came true last night: this show lives or dies on its gimmick of the week, and if the gimmick ain't cool, the Suck grows exponentially. "Elements" drags up some nonsense about Native American trinkets buried beneath Manhattan, tosses in a couple of evil businessmen from the Stock Villain files, then presumes to call it a day. Bad move..
The local Chicago gang, "South Side Chicago AntiRacist Action," has Marxist and "Black Bloc" symbols on their website. This morning they posted an announcement bragging about the Chicago restaurant attack. This group also exhibits the behavior of a hardcore criminal gang.
If you go to the web site of the manufacturer of your product and look for the product you should find any firmware updates that they may have. For example, for a LinkSys router you would go to the LinkSys web site and find the make model of the router and download the firmware package to install on your router. Instructions for installation are usually included either on the web site or in your original documentation that came with the product.
More and more horror "Bmovies" are receiving deluxe treatment on DVD, but for every cult classic being reborn on disc there are dozens of less worthy titles sitting in the vaults. Some are worth seeing, but just not as sought after, or else pristine elements aren't available. For whatever reason, many video labels want you to be able to see them, but know they can't compete in today's DVD market with solo releases.
The true performance lies somewhere in between which is why we run our real world tests that showed the V300 to be no slouch against some of the best drives on the market. During normal everyday use, one would be hard pressed to tell the difference between this and the OCZ Vector depending on their activities. Adding credence to this is the excellent performance we saw on 4k file size tests as this is more a reflection of real world data usage.
